Oh perfect timing thank you! I was just browsing around for my next series, and specifically for audiobook series.

Been wanting to get back into to doing these for a while now, here's a quick and dirty to some late summers: Like others on the sub recently I've jumped on the **Curse of Chalion by Lois McMaster Bujold,** bandwagon, but I've took this on audiobook and really glad I did so. If you read other's reviews there are lots of approval on the characterization, and it strongly driven by the leads, the feelings and experiences. I know some readers have issues with some fantasy books narrated by American accented voices, but you don't experience that as a distraction here; the certain charm, timings, pauses and quirks in the characters really stand out in the performance of Lloyd James. Also what was a surprise was the non-traditional plot I wasn't sure which way was going at certain times. A recent release non-fantasy popular seller was the creepy **Mexican Gothic by Silvia Moreno-Garcia.** This I also started in audio to get into the mood and feel, but the story stalled, started out very slow #8212;very slow. But I suppose it just fit into the dull, hazy and nauseous mood of the novel and the storytelling. I switched to traditional read ing, to speed things up, and things certainly picked up towards the end of the 2nd act and 3rd got strange really fast, so don't give up on it. Don't want to spoil anything but it is not elegant imagery. A little bothered by much of the exposition/explanation on some of the certain plot reveals, but I suppose that is to be expected without having to extend this book to 400 more pages and is more common with much of the horror/science genre. Not my favorite tale to date, a bit formulaic with much of what's going on in Hollywood and entertainment, but I do appreciate the change of environment, background and hope to see more from the author in the future. **The Memory Police by Yoko Ogawa** has not been good to me. In fact it's been the first book in a long time that has just been straight out boring and the first I had to label 'Did Not Finish' since last year. Went through the first thirteen chapters and just had to call it quits. Maybe I'll get back to it if I see someone else give a blazing review on it. One of my favorites of the summer so far has been **A Brightness Long Ago by GGK.** I don't know why I've delayed reading this for so long since I'm a huge fan of his Kay's books. This really kept me so engaged apart from his other works, since this time #8212;if I remember correctly #8212;was the first he was applying a non-linear style approach to some of the timeline and storytelling. It wasn't very drastic, but very nice change of pace as of course it applies to the title, as one might reflect back on events of the past, and in connection to current events. I didn't realize that this was a sort of prequel to **Children of Earth and Sky** as I read *'Children'* right afterwards, but it was to hardly any detriment after all. Children of Earth and Sky hasn't been one of my favorite of Kay's books, but saying that is like saying which is your least favorite diamond in your collection. With all that being said, *A Brightness Long Ago* has been one of my favorite Kay reads since A Song for Arbonne maybe. Also listened to **The House in the Cerulean Sea by TJ Klune.** This is kind of a guilty pleasure and a wholesome, feel-good read if one was looking some comfort food after all that's been happening lately. This is written for the younger ones and attempts to introduce and address some of the more complicated modern social and discriminatory issues of the day. It involves an unusual orphanage system for young outcasts, like sprites, gnomes, and wyverns. The characters are likable, the voice performances manifest themselves like Disney characters in your mind, so if you like books like the adorable **The Girl Who Drank the Moon by Kelly Barnhill,** I'm sure you'll like this as well. Right now I'm finishing up **Gideon the Ninth by Tamsy Muir** on audiobook. I'm glad I was able to hold off on this since the sequel just released today. I know there's been a divided audience on this, which is why I went with the audiobook on this and is making up for the read. I'm always a sucker for a salty, pouty, foul-mouthed and female anti-heroes; always makes for better entertainment and comes to life better on audiobooks, just like Mia Corvere on Nevernight. Anyway, halfway through, and the jury is still out. Still piecing through their necromancy magic system, but I guess I'll just let that grow on me eventually.

There were men on the bottom, a dozen of them, getting a fire started; down there, night was already descending. Here and there among them armor turned the light, and swords swung at their sides. He hardly glanced at them. Out of the clay at the bottom of the pit slanted a gigantic stone hand holding a crystal sphere, and it was this that shone with the last sunlight. Rand gaped at the size of it, a smooth ball #8212;he was sure not so much as a scratch marred its surface #8212;at least twenty paces through. #8220;Some distance away from the hand, a stone face in proportion had been uncovered. A bearded man #8217;s face, it thrust out of the soil with the dignity of vast years; the broad features seemed to hold wisdom and knowledge. Unsummoned, the void formed, whole and complete in an instant, saidin glowing, beckoning. So intent was he on the face and the hand that he did not even realize what had happened. He had once heard a ship captain speak of a giant hand holding a huge crystal sphere; Bayle Domon had claimed it stuck out of a hill on the island of Tremalking. #8220;This is dangerous, #8221; Selene said. #8220;Come away, Rand. #8221; #8220;I believe I can find a way down there, #8221; he said absently. WRITING.TEXT: [ #8220;Other hallways crossed the one he ran along, at odd angles, sometimes descending, sometimes climbing. None looked any different from the passage he was in, though. Damp stone walls unbroken by doors, and strips of darkness. As he came on one of those crossing halls, he skidded to a halt. A man stood there, blinking at him uncertainly, in strangely cut coat and breeches, the coat flaring over his hips as the bottoms of the breeches flared over his boots. Both were bright yellow, and his boots were only a little paler. #8220;Who are you? #8221; Perrin asked. The man #8217;s eyebrows rose as if he were offended. The strips of shadow around them writhed. One detached from the ceiling at one end and drifted down to touch the strange man #8217;s head. It appeared to tangle in his hair. The man #8217;s eyes widened, and everything seemed to happen at once. The shadow jerked back to the ceiling, ten feet overhead, trailing something pale. Wet drops splattered Perrin #8217;s face. A bone-rattling shriek shattered the air. #8221; -*The Dragon Reborn, Chapter 9*](https://www.instagram.com/p/BjZEHrxhMzR/)
